TI  == vulvovaginitis in childhood.
AB  == symptoms related to vulvitis and vulvovaginitis are a frequent complaint in the paediatric age. knowledge of the risk factors and the pathogenetic mechanisms, combined with thorough clinical examination, helps to distinguish between dermatological diseases, non-specific vulvitis and vulvovaginitis proper. on the  basis of microbiological data, the most common pathogens prove to be streptococcus pyogenes, haemophilus influenzae and enterobius vermicularis; fungal and viral infections are less frequent. the possibility of isolating opportunistic pathogens should also be considered. in rare situations, the isolation of a micro-organism normally transmitted by sexual contact should prompt a careful evaluation of possible sexual abuse. current treatments for specific and non-specific forms are outlined, together with pointers for the evaluation of recurrence.
